<h3 id="reading-assignments">Reading assignments</h3>
<p>The reading assignments have two parts: reading some sections from of the book, and then doing a few exercises to help establish a basic understanding of the concepts introduced in those sections.</p>
<p>To show that you did the reading assignment, you‚Äôll use an online form to submit a question that you have about the reading, and to indicate that you have completed the exercises associated with the reading assignment. For the day A reading assignment, you‚Äôll submit this form by 11:59pm the night <em>before</em> day A, and then you‚Äôll submit a hard copy of the exercises at the beginning of class on day A.</p>
<p>A few thoughts about these submissions:</p>
<ul>
<li><p>Remember that you don‚Äôt necessarily need to wait till the night before day A to work on and submit the reading assignment for day A. You‚Äôre strongly encouraged to get ahead. I‚Äôve often found that letting things simmer in the back of my mind for a while helps me understand them.</p></li>
<li><p>You might be asking, ‚ÄúWhat if I don‚Äôt have any questions about the reading?!‚Äù That‚Äôs fine. You can submit a non-question instead. For example, you might decide to send me a question that you had, but then you managed to figure out (either by yourself or by asking someone for help). Or you might send me something that you understand but you think one of your peers might find confusing. I‚Äôm mostly looking for an indication that you read the assigned reading and made a sincere attempt to process it.</p></li>
<li><p>I‚Äôll do my best to tailor our in-class discussions to address as many of your questions as I can. The earlier you send me your question, the more likely I am to be able to work it into our discussions. If I don‚Äôt adequately address your question in class, please find me during office hours and ask again!</p></li>
<li><p>I‚Äôll check your solutions to the reading assignment exercises only for completeness. Hefferon provides an answer key for all of the exercises in the textbook, and you are encouraged to check your solutions for correctness yourself.</p></li>
</ul>
<h3 id="in-class-structure">In-class structure</h3>
<p>I‚Äôll begin class with a very brief discussion of the reading. This is not intended to be a substitute for having done the reading. Instead, the idea is to refresh your memory about what we‚Äôll be discussing in class today by working through a couple of examples.</p>
<p>We‚Äôll spend most of class time solving problems in the following format.</p>
<ul>
<li>I‚Äôll put a problem on the board.</li>
<li>You‚Äôll think about the problem by yourself for a couple of minutes.</li>
<li>We‚Äôll vote on an answer to the problem.</li>
<li>You‚Äôll have a few minutes to talk to your classmates about the problem.</li>
<li>We‚Äôll vote again.</li>
<li>I‚Äôll tell you how I‚Äôd solve the problem.</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="problem-sets">Problem sets</h3>
